This rice-planting dance is a {{ill|yoshuku-geino|ja|予祝芸能|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yoshuku-geino|qq=}} (ritual performance for blessings of bountiful harvests) originating from four {{ill|settlements|ja|集落|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/settlements|qq=}} in Tsushima: Kamitsushima, Shimotsushima, Minamitsushima, and Akaogi. It was traditionally performed on the {{ill|14th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月14日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/14th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}, {{ill|15th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/15th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}, and {{ill|17th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月17日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/17th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}. Today, the dance is performed according to the Gregorian calendar. On the 14th, it is first offered at each settlement's {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}}, followed by performances at requested households.
The performers include: * '''Kuwakashira''' (鍬頭): Dressed in {{ill|naga-juban|ja|長襦袢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/naga-juban|qq=}} and tied with {{ill|donko|ja|緞子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/donko|qq=}}, wearing a twisted {{ill|tenugui|ja|手拭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tenugui|qq=}} headband and carrying a large gourd. * '''Tane-oroshi''' (種下ろし): Two singers dressed in {{ill|formal kimono|ja|紋付羽織袴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/formal kimono|qq=}}, armed with a {{ill|wakizashi|ja|脇差|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wakizashi|qq=}} and holding {{ill|sensu|ja|扇子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sensu|qq=}}. * '''Taiko-uchi''' (太鼓打ち): Two drummers wearing {{ill|formal hakama|ja|袷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/formal hakama|qq=}} tied with a {{ill|yaku-obi|ja|奴帯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yaku-obi|qq=}}, with rolled-up kimono hems, white {{ill|mohimo|ja|股引|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mohimo|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kyahan|ja|脚絆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyahan|qq=}}, carrying {{ill|taiko|ja|太鼓|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/taiko|qq=}} and sticks. * '''Sasara-zuri''' (ささら摺り): Two boys aged 14–15 wearing {{ill|kasuri|ja|絣|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kasuri|qq=}} garments, equipped with {{ill|Binzasara|ja|ささら|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Binzasara|qq=}} (wooden clappers). * '''Saotome''' (早乙女): Several adult male performers in {{ill|Edo-tsuma|ja|江戸褄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo-tsuma|qq=}} kimono, wearing {{ill|Okoso zukin|ja|おこそ頭巾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okoso zukin|qq=}} hoods and holding {{ill|yotsutake|ja|四つ竹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yotsutake|qq=}} or sensu.
The performance begins with a speech by the Kuwakashira, followed by dance sequences symbolizing "Seed Sowing," "Rice Planting," "Harvesting," "Threshing," "Milling," "Winnowing," and "Ending Ceremony." The ritual concludes with the Kuwakashira delivering congratulatory remarks.
== References == * "Matsuri, Geinō, Gyōji Daijiten (Vol. 2)" (朝倉書店, 2009), ISBN 978-4-254-50013-4.
