==Merged second translation== '''Tsushima no Taue Odori''' (津島の田植踊) is a {{ill|rice-planting dance|ja|田植踊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/rice-planting dance|qq=}}, a form of folk performing art, passed down in {{ill|Tsunami, Namie|ja|浪江町津島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsunami, Namie|qq=}}, [[:en:Namie, Fukushima|Namie, Fukushima]], located in [[:en:Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima Prefecture]], Japan. It has been designated as a {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|選択無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} by the national government and as a {{ill|Prefectural Cultural Property of Japan|ja|都道府県指定無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Cultural Property of Japan|qq=}} by Fukushima Prefecture.
This rice-planting dance is a {{ill|Yoshuku|lt=Yoshuku|lt=Yoshuku-geino|ja|予祝芸能|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yoshuku-geino|qq=}} (ritual performance for blessings of bountiful harvests) originating from four [[:en:Human settlement|settlements]] in Tsushima: Kamitsushima, Shimotsushima, Minamitsushima, and Akaogi. It was traditionally performed on the {{ill|14th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月14日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/14th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}, {{ill|15th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/15th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}, and {{ill|17th day of the 1st lunar month|ja|1月17日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/17th day of the 1st lunar month|qq=}}. Today, the dance is performed according to the Gregorian calendar. On the 14th, it is first offered at each settlement's [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]], followed by performances at requested households.
The performers include: * '''Kuwakashira''' (鍬頭): Dressed in {{ill|naga-juban|ja|長襦袢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/naga-juban|qq=}} and tied with {{ill|donko|ja|緞子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/donko|qq=}}, wearing a twisted [[:en:Tenugui|tenugui]] headband and carrying a large gourd. * '''Tane-oroshi''' (種下ろし): Two singers dressed in {{ill|formal kimono|ja|紋付羽織袴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/formal kimono|qq=}}, armed with a [[:en:Wakizashi|wakizashi]] and holding [[:en:Hand fan|sensu]]. * '''Taiko-uchi''' (太鼓打ち): Two drummers wearing {{ill|formal hakama|ja|袷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/formal hakama|qq=}} tied with a {{ill|yaku-obi|ja|奴帯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yaku-obi|qq=}}, with rolled-up kimono hems, white {{ill|mohimo|ja|股引|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mohimo|qq=}}, and [[:en:Kyahan|Kyahan]], carrying [[:en:Drum|taiko]] and sticks. * '''Sasara-zuri''' (ささら摺り): Two boys aged 14–15 wearing [[:en:Kasuri|kasuri]] garments, equipped with [[:en:Binzasara|Binzasara]] (wooden clappers). * '''Saotome''' (早乙女): Several adult male performers in {{ill|Edo-tsuma|ja|江戸褄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo-tsuma|qq=}} kimono, wearing {{ill|Okoso zukin|ja|おこそ頭巾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okoso zukin|qq=}} hoods and holding {{ill|yotsutake|ja|四つ竹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yotsutake|qq=}} or sensu.
The performance begins with a speech by the Kuwakashira, followed by dance sequences symbolizing "Seed Sowing," "Rice Planting," "Harvesting," "Threshing," "Milling," "Winnowing," and "Ending Ceremony." The ritual concludes with the Kuwakashira delivering congratulatory remarks.
== References == * "Matsuri, Geinō, Gyōji Daijiten (Vol. 2)" (朝倉書店, 2009), ISBN 978-4-254-50013-4.
