[[Category:Merged pages]] [[Category:qq]]<!--Doing this to bump these pages because my history retrieval attempts have led to category caching errors-->[[sn:Tsubame Taue Odori]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:予祝芸能]] [[Category:東北地方開催の冬季イベント]] [[Category:Namie, Fukushima]] [[Category:Festivals of Fukushima prefecture]] [[Category:Intangible Folk Cultural Properties that need measures such as documentation of Japan]] [[Category:Prefecturally designated intangible folk cultural property]]

'''Tsushima no Taue Odori''' (津島の田植踊) is a traditional folk performance of rice planting dance from {{ill|Tsunami, Namie, Fukushima|ja|福島県双葉郡浪江町津島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsunami, Namie, Fukushima|qq=}}, Japan. It is recognized as a {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|選択無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} by the national government and as a prefectural {{ill|Designated Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Designated Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} of Fukushima Prefecture.
This rice planting dance is a form of {{ill|Yoshuku|lt=Yoshuku|lt=Yoshuku performing arts|ja|予祝芸能|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshuku performing arts|qq=}} that prays for abundant harvests, passed down through four villages in Namie: Kamitsushima, Shimotsushima, Minamitsushima, and Akugun. It was traditionally performed on {{ill|January 14th (lunar calendar)|ja|1月14日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 14th (lunar calendar)|qq=}}, {{ill|January 15th (lunar calendar)|ja|1月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 15th (lunar calendar)|qq=}}, and {{ill|January 17th (lunar calendar)|ja|1月17日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 17th (lunar calendar)|qq=}} but is now conducted according to the Gregorian calendar. On the first day, January 14th, the dance is dedicated at each village's respective [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shrine]], followed by performances at houses upon request.
The performance features distinct roles: * '''Kuwagashira''' (鍬頭): The leader who wears a {{ill|Nagajuban|ja|長襦袢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagajuban|qq=}}, secures a brocade sash (緞子), twists a [[:en:Tenugui|Tenugui]] around their head, and carries a large calabash. * '''Taneoroshi''' (種下ろし): Two performers in {{ill|Mon-tsuki haori hakama|ja|紋付羽織袴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mon-tsuki haori hakama|qq=}}, equi11ed with short swords and folding fans, who sing. * '''Taiko-uchi''' (太鼓打ち): Two performers in mon-tsuki, tied with a {{ill|Yaku-himo|ja|奴帯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yaku-himo|qq=}}, who wear white {{ill|Matabiki|ja|股引|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matabiki|qq=}} and gaiters, playing drums with sticks. * '''Sasara-suri''' (ささら摺り): Two performers in [[:en:Kasuri|Kasuri]] kimono, wearing short pants, and holding bamboo cla11ers (sasara). These roles are played by boys aged 14–15, while all other roles are performed by adult men. * '''Saotome''' (早乙女): Several performers wearing Edo-style tsumugi kimono and {{ill|Okoso zukin|ja|おこそ頭巾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okoso zukin|qq=}} headdresses, carrying small fans and four-legged bamboo sticks.
The dance begins with the Kuwagashira's prologue and progresses through themes such as "Seed Planting," "Rice Planting," "Harvesting," "Threshing," "Hulling," "Using the Winnowing Machine," and "Ritual Completion tier 3]] {{Japan-culture-stub}}
}}
